@Rahul

For one thing, it's TOKENS, not TOpENS.  You mistakenly put PEEp for PEEK.  When NYC first opened the subway in (I think) 1904, it cost five cents (one coin).  Eventually, it went up to ten cents (still one coin). When it eventually went up to 15 cents, the coin slots on the (turn)stile could accommodate two separate coins. Thus the subway TOKEN was born.  The TOKEN was replaced by the Metrocard, and then, a new app-based system called OMNY where you pay with a tap of your phone.

Anyway, the rest of the stuff that tripped you up would be known by a reasonably educated and well-read American.  Some of those things do not travel well to Southeast Asia.  OREL Hershiser was a major league baseball star a generation or two ago.  NLRB is National Labor Relations Board.  It's understandable how many of these things and people are not as well known outside the US.

@Jezz

You probably put in just the first letter of the rebus [IDE] in the middle of the word.  Sadly, the program accepts this (incorrect) answer due to complaints from USERS who couldn't figure out how to enter rebuses.

The correct answer is A[IDE]D, not AID.

